er, publisher, and vendor of his own books. In his early career as a commercial engraver, Blake was modestly prosperous, but thereafter his fortunes declined. For his most ambitious commercial designs, he made hundreds of folio designs and scores of engravings, but was paid scarcely more than twenty pounds for two or three years' work. His invention of illuminated printing lost money, and many of his greatest works, such as Jerusalem, were left unsold at his death. He came to believe that his "business is not to gather gold, but to make glorious shapes." William Blake in the Desolate Market is an investigation of Blake's labours to support himself by his arts. The changing prices of his works, his costs and receipts, as well as his patrons and employers are expertly gathered and displayed to show the material side of the artistic career in Britain's Romantic period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlake, William 1757-1827xBlake, William 1757-1827xFinance, PersonalxBlake, William 1757-1827xEngraversxBiographyzGreat BritainxPoets, EnglishxBiographyy18th centuryxEngraversxFinance, PersonalxPoets, EnglishzGreat BritainvBiography. 0aEngravers - Great Britain. 0aEngraverszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aPoets, Englishy18th centuryvBiography. 7aART / Individual Artists / Monographs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359029840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773590298423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773590298/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles